JOHANNESBURG – Steinhoff International has been dealt yet another blow. Credit insurers are withdrawing cover for the troubled retailer’s international loans.
	
	The company’s Austrian subsidiary, Kika-Leiner said in a statement the move is a result of the company’s current crisis. READ: How Steinhoff execs cooked the books Steinhoff which shed over 90 percent of its value since accounting irregularities emerged late last year is also facing multiple lawsuits. Earlier this year, Kika-Leiner had said it secured enough cash to sustain it for the rest of the year. It’s now been given until the end of the week to find a solution. eNCA